We use the change of variables from cartesian coordinates to polar
coordinates\begin{align*}
\displaystyle \begin{pmatrix}x\\y\end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix}r\cos(\phi)\\r\sin(\phi)\end{pmatrix}
\end{align*}

The region of integration in polar coordinates is
$\displaystyle D=\{(r,\phi)|\ r\in[0,\sqrt{2}],\ \phi\in[0,\frac{\pi}{4}]\}$.
The function $\displaystyle y\sqrt{x^2+y^2}$ becomes
$\displaystyle r^2\sin(\phi)$. The volume factor for polar coordinates
is $\displaystyle r$. Hence,

\begin{align*}
\iint_Dy\sqrt{x^2+y^2}\;\text{d}A &= \int_0^{\sqrt{2}}\int_0^{\frac{\pi}{4}}r^2\sin(\phi)r\;\text{d}\phi\text{d}r\\
&= \int_0^{\sqrt{2}}r^3[-\cos(\phi)]_0^{\frac\pi4}\;\text{d}r\\
&= \left[\frac14r^4\right]_0^{\sqrt{2}}(-\cos(\frac\pi4) + \cos(0))\\
&= 1-\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}
\end{align*}
